data.body:
This is a suggestion: the space for line numbers in the gutter should be at least two characters wide, so that the transition from 9 lines to 10 doesn't change the gutter width. 

The reasoning goes like this: this transition happens when we've just started writing a new file, it is quite likely (few files are below 9 lines), and can be a distracting unexpected movement in peripheral vision. 

I was torn out of concentration by this sudden movement once too many times, so now I have this in my `styles.less`:

``` less
atom-text-editor {
  &,
  &::shadow {
    .gutter .line-number {
      min-width: 4.5ch; // 4.5 and not 2 because there's something else there, too
    }
  }
}
```

But that feels sub-optimal.

Even better (but much harder to implement) would be a width that smoothly increases (it could be set to _log10(lines)+1_ ch, again minimum 2ch) so that gutter width never jumps during normal editing.

Refs #8350

Regardless of whether you're holding `shift` or `cmd`, the autoscroll behavior should be consistent.

@izuzak Can you try to break this?

![waaat](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/38924/9253901/dad3ef26-41e0-11e5-88f9-4120247b25af.gif)

I select some text, press `r` (or some other key), and the selected text is replaced with `r`, but the selection stays behind and is now selecting some other text. I'm in safe mode, Atom 1.0.8-469662a, OSX 10.10.4.

@nathansobo @benogle @maxbrunsfeld Any of you seeing the same thing and know what might be up? Doesn't happen on all selections but it seems to always happen when there's some text like `foo bar, baz`, and then I drag-select `bar` (up to but not including the `,`), and then press a key to replace the selection.
